        "body": "### 1. Workdays: 100 → 125\n\nThe headline change is straightforward: the statutory guarantee rises from 100 days per rural household per financial year to 125 days. In practice, however, the average household under MGNREGA received only about 50 days of work per year — far below even the old 100-day ceiling.\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: Jean Drèze and Rahul R, \"A Short History of MGNREGA: Twenty Years in Ten Charts,\" Levy Economics Institute Working Paper No. 1095, October 2025. Confidence: 95.\n\nWhether the 125-day guarantee translates into more actual workdays depends on budget allocations and state implementation capacity — both of which are now structured differently under the new Act.\n\n### 2. Wage Floor: First-Time National Minimum\n\nThe government introduced an **interim base wage of ₹300 per day** — the first statutory wage floor in the programme's history. The national average wage was simultaneously raised to ₹327.4 per day. Twenty-one states and union territories that previously paid below ₹300 were brought up to the new floor.\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: Ministry of Rural Development notification, June 30, 2026; News18, July 1, 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\nState-wise wages under VB-G RAM G (effective July 1, 2026):\n\n| State / UT | Revised Daily Wage (₹) |\n|---|---|\n| Sikkim (High Altitude Gram Panchayats) | 450 |\n| Haryana | 409 |\n| Goa | 406 |\n| Kerala | 401 |\n| Karnataka | 382 |\n| Himachal Pradesh (Scheduled Areas) | 375 |\n| Punjab | 360 |\n| Tamil Nadu | 345 |\n| Himachal Pradesh (Non-Scheduled Areas) | 328 |\n| Maharashtra | 317 |\n| Andhra Pradesh | 312 |\n| Telangana | 308 |\n| 21 states/UTs at floor rate (UP, Bihar, WB, Rajasthan, MP, Odisha, Jharkhand, Gujarat, Assam, Chhattisgarh, others) | 300 |\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: Ministry of Rural Development wage notification; News18 state-wise table; Times of India, July 1, 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\nThe largest percentage increases went to states with historically lowest wages — Arunachal Pradesh and Nagaland saw nearly 24.5% hikes. States that already paid above the floor (Kerala, Haryana, Punjab, Karnataka) received smaller indexation-linked increases.\n\n### 3. Funding Structure: From 90:10 to 60:40\n\nThis is the most consequential change — and the most contested.\n\nUnder MGNREGA, the Union government bore 100% of wage costs and 75% of material costs, resulting in an effective 90:10 cost-sharing ratio between Centre and states. Under VB-G RAM G:\n\n- **North-Eastern and Himalayan states**: 90:10 (Centre:State)\n- **Other states and UTs with legislature**: 60:40\n- **UTs without legislature**: 100% central funding\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: VB-G RAM G Act, 2025, Section 12; PIB FAQ document, May 2026; Indian Express, May 27, 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\nThis means most states must now contribute 40% of total programme expenditure — a fourfold increase in their financial responsibility. Five opposition-ruled states — Karnataka, Kerala, Punjab, Telangana, and Jharkhand — have passed resolutions opposing the Act.\n\n**Political Claim.** Source: Scroll.in, July 1, 2026; News18. States cited: Karnataka (Congress), Kerala (CPI(M)-led LDF), Punjab (AAP), Telangana (Congress), Jharkhand (JMM-Congress). Confidence: 100.\n\n### 4. Allocation Model: Demand-Driven → Supply-Driven\n\nUnder MGNREGA, the programme was demand-driven: if a household demanded work, the government was legally obligated to provide it, and the budget had to follow. The Act appropriated funds \"as may be required\" — meaning there was no fixed upper limit.\n\n**Historical Record.** Source: MGNREGA Act, 2005, Section 23; Parliamentary budget documents, various years. Confidence: 100.\n\nVB-G RAM G replaces this with a **normative allocation model**. The Centre determines each state's allocation based on \"objective parameters\" — including the Sixteenth Finance Commission's horizontal devolution formula — and any expenditure beyond that allocation must be borne entirely by the state.\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: VB-G RAM G Act, 2025, Section 5; draft Objective Parameters for Normative Allocation Rules, 2026; Indian Express, May 27, 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\nThis change transforms the nature of the guarantee. Critics argue it is no longer a legal entitlement backed by central funding, but a fixed-budget programme with state-level top-up risk.\n\n**Expert Opinion.** Source: The Hindu, June 29, 2026 — \"Why are States opposing VB-G RAM G\"; economists cited by BusinessLine, May 11, 2026. Confidence: 90.\n\n### 5. Agricultural Blackout Period\n\nThe Act permits the government to notify a period of up to **60 non-working days** during peak agricultural seasons — effectively allowing the programme to be paused when farm labour demand is high. Under MGNREGA, workers could seek employment year-round, without seasonal exclusions.\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: VB-G RAM G Act, 2025, Section 8(3); The Hindu, June 29, 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\nAt least four states — Punjab, Karnataka, Telangana, and Kerala — have sought reconsideration of this provision, arguing it reduces earning opportunities for landless labourers who depend on MGNREGA even during agricultural seasons.\n\n### 6. Technology and Transparency\n\nThe Act mandates:\n- **Face-authentication attendance** for workers — replacing manual muster rolls\n- **Geo-referencing** of all worksites\n- **Direct Benefit Transfer** of wages to bank or post office accounts\n- Mandatory **social audits** every six months per gram panchayat\n- Delay compensation at **0.05% per day** for unpaid wages beyond 15 days\n- Unemployment allowance at **1/4th of wage for first 30 days**, **1/2 for remainder**\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: VB-G RAM G Act, 2025, Sections 14-18; PIB FAQ, May 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\nCivil society organisations have raised concerns that mandatory face authentication could exclude elderly workers and those in areas with poor digital connectivity.\n\n**Expert Opinion.** Source: Economic Times, May 11, 2026; The Hindu, June 29, 2026. Confidence: 90."
