        "body": "### The Government's Case\n\nThe government presents VB-G RAM G as a modernization of a two-decade-old law. Rural Development Minister Shivraj Singh Chouhan described it as \"a historic step towards building a Viksit Bharat through prosperous villages.\" The key arguments:\n\n- **Higher wages**: \"We have ensured better wages for rural workers. The largest increase has been provided to states where wages were historically low, so those who need the greatest support benefit the most.\" — Shivraj Singh Chouhan, July 1, 2026.\n- **More workdays**: The 125-day guarantee is a 25% increase in the legal entitlement.\n- **Fiscal discipline**: Normative allocation prevents budget overruns and ensures predictable funding.\n- **Technology**: Face authentication and geo-tagging reduce leakages and ghost workers.\n- **Agricultural sensitivity**: The blackout period ensures labour availability during peak farming seasons.\n\n**Official Statement.** Source: Ministry of Rural Development press release, July 1, 2026; Times of India, July 1, 2026. Confidence: 100.\n\n### The Opposition's Case\n\nFive opposition-ruled states have passed resolutions against the Act. Critics raise four principal objections:\n\n- **Financial burden on states**: The shift from 90:10 to 60:40 disproportionately affects states with higher rural populations and weaker fiscal positions. Bihar, which had the lowest MGNREGA wage (₹241), now must find 40% of a larger programme cost.\n- **End of demand-driven guarantee**: \"It is no longer a right-based entitlement but a centrally capped allocation. If demand exceeds the normative allocation, the state must pay — effectively negating the guarantee.\" — Analysis in The Hindu, June 29, 2026.\n- **Centralisation**: Section 5(1) empowers the Centre to notify \"rural areas in a State\" where the scheme applies — departing from MGNREGA's universal coverage. This raises concerns that the scheme could be selectively applied.\n- **Blackout period**: Reducing earning opportunities for landless labourers during agricultural seasons, when they often need supplementary income the most.\n\n**Political Claim / Expert Opinion.** Source: The Hindu, June 29, 2026; Scroll.in, July 1, 2026; BusinessLine, May 11, 2026. Confidence: 95.\n\n### The Data\n\nMGNREGA at a glance — the programme being replaced:\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Households registered (2024-25) | 15.99 crore |\n| Person-days generated (2024-25) | 290.60 crore |\n| Average days per household | ~50 (far below 100-day ceiling) |\n| Women's participation (2024-25) | 58.15% (440.7 lakh women) |\n| Budget allocation (2025-26 BE) | ₹86,000 crore |\n| Peak budget (2020-21) | ₹1,11,500 crore (COVID year) |\n| Central expenditure as % of GDP | 0.3-0.4% (from 0.6% peak in 2009-10) |\n| Assets created (by March 2025) | 86.98 lakh |\n| Administrative cost share | Fell from ~6% to ~3-4% of total expenditure (2014-15 onward) |\n| Lowest notified wage (pre-July 2026) | ₹241/day in Bihar |\n| Highest notified wage (pre-July 2026) | ₹374/day in Haryana |\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: PIB, August 2025; Drèze & Rahul R, Levy Institute WP 1095, October 2025; MGNREGA MIS; Outlook India, December 2025. Confidence: 95."
