        "type": "whats-next",
        "title": "The Bigger Picture",
        "body": "### 20 Years of MGNREGA: A Brief History\n\nThe Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Act was passed on September 7, 2005 — a flagship of the Congress-led United Progressive Alliance government, championed by Sonia Gandhi's National Advisory Council. It rolled out in three phases:\n\n- **February 2006**: 200 most backward districts\n- **2007**: 330 additional districts\n- **April 2008**: All 619 rural districts of India\n- **2009**: Renamed from NREGA to MGNREGA (Mahatma Gandhi appended)\n\nOver two decades, MGNREGA evolved from a rural employment programme into something larger: a countercyclical stabiliser, a women's empowerment tool, and a legal precedent for the right to work. During the COVID-19 crisis in 2020-21, it generated a record 389 crore person-days and absorbed millions of returning migrants.\n\n**Historical Record.** Source: Drèze & Rahul R, Levy Institute WP 1095; PIB historical releases; Parliament records. Confidence: 100.\n\nYet the programme faced persistent criticism: average days per household stagnated around 50 (half the legal entitlement), wage payments were frequently delayed, administrative spending was cut sharply after 2014-15, and budget releases often fell short of actual demand despite the legal obligation to fund it.\n\n### India's Employment Challenge\n\nThe replacement of MGNREGA comes at a time when India's rural economy is under multiple pressures: agricultural fragmentation, climate-induced distress, stagnant real wages, and insufficient non-farm employment. The unemployment rate in rural India was 5.5% as of May 2026 (PLFS). Youth unemployment — especially among educated rural youth — runs significantly higher.\n\n**Verified Fact.** Source: PLFS Bulletin, May 2026; Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation. Confidence: 95.\n\nEconomists argue that the key question is not whether 125 days is better than 100, but whether the new funding model will enable or constrain the programme's countercyclical role — its ability to expand precisely when the economy contracts and private employment disappears.\n\n**Expert Opinion.** Source: Drèze & Rahul R, Levy Institute WP 1095; Outlook India analysis, December 2025. Confidence: 90.\n\n### International Context\n\nIndia is not alone in rethinking employment guarantee programmes. Argentina's Jefes de Hogar plan, South Africa's Expanded Public Works Programme, and pilot programmes in the United States have all grappled with similar tensions between legal entitlements and fiscal constraints. The VB-G RAM G model — shifting from demand-driven to supply-driven — moves India closer to a fixed-budget public works model and away from the rights-based framework that made MGNREGA distinctive internationally.\n\n**Independent Verification.** Source: Levy Economics Institute research on job guarantee programmes; ILO World Social Protection Report, 2024-26. Confidence: 80."
