        "body": "Polymer-modified bitumen, which mixes plastic waste into asphalt, produces roads that last two to three times longer than conventional surfaces. Cold-mix asphalt allows pothole repairs in the rain. Geotextile reinforcement prevents reflective cracking. Sensor-based road assessment vehicles can survey entire state highway networks in days.\n\nAll of these technologies are commercially available in India. Many have been mandated in central government guidelines for years. The National Rural Roads Development Agency has published detailed specifications for climate-resilient pavement design. The Indian Roads Congress has issued codes for every conceivable road type and climatic zone.\n\nThe gap between what is specified and what is actually built is not a technical gap. It is a gap in enforcement."
