        "title": "The Real Problem: Governance",
        "body": "Road construction and maintenance in India is contracted through a tender system with deep structural flaws. Contracts are awarded to the lowest bidder almost by default. The lowest bidder has every incentive to cut corners — thinner asphalt layers, poorer compaction, substandard materials — because inspections are weak and penalties for poor workmanship are rarely imposed.\n\nWhen a road fails within the defect liability period — typically five years for national highways — the contractor is supposed to bear the repair cost. In practice, contractors exploit legal loopholes, arbitration delays, and political connections to avoid liability. A 2024 Comptroller and Auditor General report found that over ₹12,000 crore in penalty amounts were pending recovery from defaulting road contractors across just ten states.\n\nThe other half of the governance problem is maintenance funding. Indian states spend roughly 0.5 per cent of their road asset value on maintenance each year, against a recommended benchmark of 2 to 3 per cent. The shortfall means that even well-built roads deteriorate rapidly once small cracks appear — there is no money to seal them before monsoon season turns them into craters."
