    "body": "<h1>Meta AI Mode: 2 Billion Users, No Opt-Out</h1>\n<h2>Cold Open</h2>\n<p>On June 17, Meta replaced traditional search with AI-generated answers across Facebook, Instagram, and WhatsApp — affecting roughly 2 billion users with no consent prompt, no opt-out mechanism, and no advance notice. Powered by Meta&#39;s Muse Spark model, the feature synthesises information from public posts, web content, and Meta&#39;s knowledge graph to generate text, answer questions, and recommend content without leaving the app. It is the largest AI deployment in history, and most users never consented to it.</p>\n<h2>What Changed</h2>\n<p>Meta AI Mode replaces chronological and algorithmic search results with AI-generated responses. Facebook&#39;s 1 billion-plus daily active users, Instagram&#39;s 500 million-plus, and WhatsApp Business&#39;s 200 million-plus now all default to the new search paradigm. Users who want traditional search must manually toggle a setting that Meta has buried multiple layers deep in the menu structure. The change applies platform-wide with no per-user opt-in.</p>\n<h2>The Privacy Question</h2>\n<p>Meta has trained its AI models on public Facebook and Instagram posts since at least 2023, but AI Mode goes further: it actively surfaces AI-generated answers based on user data in real time. There is no setting to opt out of AI Mode search results entirely. Privacy advocates identify four specific concerns: no informed consent for the change, AI responses that incorporate user-generated content without attribution, no mechanism for users to exclude their data, and a deliberately difficult opt-out path. The deployment tests the limits of Meta&#39;s existing data-processing consent under Indian and European regulations.</p>\n<h2>The Competitive Landscape</h2>\n<p>Meta AI Mode puts Facebook in direct competition with Google&#39;s AI Overviews, ChatGPT Search, and Amazon Rufus — all four now default to AI-generated answers. Meta&#39;s differentiator is access to 2 billion users&#39; social graphs, interaction patterns, and personal data, giving it a unique advantage in personalising AI responses. The competitive question is whether personalised AI search will drive engagement or trigger a regulatory backlash that forces platforms to offer choice.</p>\n<h2>What It Means</h2>\n<p>The biggest AI deployment in history happened without fanfare, without regulation, and without user consent. For 2 billion people, AI is no longer a separate tool — it is now the default interface for finding information on the world&#39;s largest social platforms. The question is not whether AI will shape how people access information; it already does. The question is who controls that shift, and whether users have any say in the matter. Between Meta&#39;s deployment scale and its deliberate design choice to deny opt-out, the answer, for now, is clear.</p>\n"
