        "title": "Global Context",
        "body": "India's guidelines enter a crowded and fragmented regulatory landscape. The EU has a binding AI Act; China has a state-centric approach with licensing for algorithms and generative AI; the US has no federal law. India's principle-based, voluntary fourth path seeks to balance innovation with accountability while asserting digital sovereignty. The approach positions India as a potential model for other developing nations navigating AI regulation — offering a framework that is rigorous enough to build trust but flexible enough to adapt to rapid technological change. The question is whether voluntary compliance will be sufficient, or whether the absence of binding enforcement will eventually force India toward harder regulation as AI deployment scales."
